## Conflict Rate Monitoring
```python
# Track conflict rate weekly — high conflict = signals mis-calibrated
# Target: conflict rate < 15% of non-neutral evaluations

def compute_conflict_rate(signal_log: list[dict]) -> float:
    non_neutral = [s for s in signal_log
                   if s["obi_direction"] != "neutral" and s["roc_direction"] != "neutral"]
    conflicts   = [s for s in non_neutral if s["skip_reason"] == "SIGNAL_CONFLICT"]
    return len(conflicts) / len(non_neutral) if non_neutral else 0.0

# If conflict_rate > 0.20 → thresholds may be miscalibrated, escalate to QR
```

## Guardrails
- The coordination table is the only place signal interaction is defined — never hardcode conflict logic elsewhere
- Adding a new signal requires expanding the full matrix — partial additions cause undefined behavior
- Conviction.HIGH should represent 20–40% of actual trade entries — if it's higher, thresholds are too loose
- Never bypass the resolver to submit an order directly — all orders must flow through resolve()
